{
  "doc_id": "44373",
  "text": "The bacterial colonies were detected with an inverted microscope (Nikon GM3) and typical L-form colonies appeared as 'fried eggs' along with normal growth on the control medium without penicillin. For Gram stain, one L-form colony and one N-form colony were removed with toothpicks and ground into a drop of PBS on the slide. The bacteria were Gram-stained [CITATION_1] and then observed under a microscope (Olympus). Typical colonies were fixed with glutaraldehyde before being processed and examined by transmission electron microscopy (TEM; JEM-1230) and scanning electron microscopy (SEM; JSM-6380Lv) using procedures as described [CITATION_2] Shingaki et al., 2003) .",
